2. **`Assert.AreEqual(object, object)` overload removed** — your `GetOrder_NullId_ThrowsException` test uses `object`-typed variables, which will fail to compile in v3

## Changes needed:

**TestProject.csproj** — remove the assembly reference, add MSTest v3:

```xml
<Project Sdk="Microsoft.NET.Sdk">
  <PropertyGroup>
    <TargetFramework>net462</TargetFramework>
    <IsPackable>false</IsPackable>
  </PropertyGroup>

  <ItemGroup>
    <PackageReference Include="MSTest" Version="3.8.0" />
    <PackageReference Include="Microsoft.NET.Test.Sdk" Version="17.13.0" />
  </ItemGroup>
</Project>
```

**OrderServiceTests.cs** — fix the `object`-typed assertion:

```csharp
// Before (compiles in v1/v2, fails in v3):
object expected = "hello";
object actual = "hello";
Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual);

// After:
Assert.AreEqual<object>(expected, actual);
// Or better, use the actual type:
string expected = "hello";
string actual = "hello";
Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual);
```

**`[Timeout(5000)]`** still works but behavior is now unified across .NET Core and Framework — verify it behaves as expected.

